<statement><div><p>The diagram shows a simplified circuit in which two independent components <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are connected in parallel.</p><p/><p style="text-align: center;"><image alt="" width="28%" class="img-responsive atto_image_button_text-bottom" source="stack/images/stk-circuits-using-probability-figure1.pdf"/></p><p/><p>The circuit functions if either or both of the components are operational. It is known that if <m>A</m> is the event 'component <m>a</m> is operating' and <m>B</m> is the event 'component <m>b</m> is operating' then <m>\text{P}(A)=0.{95}</m>, <m>\text{P}(B)=0.{97}</m> and <m>\text{P}(A\cap B)=0.{94}</m>.<nbsp/> Find the probability that the circuit is functioning.</p><p><fillin characters="15" name="ans1"/> </p></div></statement>
<solution><div><p>The probability that the circuit is functioning is <m>\text{P}(A\cup B)</m>. In words: either <m>a</m> or <m>b</m> or</p><p>both must be functioning if the circuit is to function. Using the keypoint:</p><p><md number="yes">
<mrow>\text{P}(A\cup B)\amp =\amp \text{P}(A)+\text{P}(B)-\text{P}(A\cap B)</mrow>
<mrow>\amp =\amp 0.{95}+0.{97}-0.{94}=0.{98}</mrow>
</md></p></div></solution>
<answer><p><m>0.98</m></p></answer>
</stack-static>